AGI -&nbsp;The United Nations General Assembly could this evening improve Palestinian status at the United Nations, guaranteeing almost all rights of constitutionality within its plenum, except to allow it to vote. Jerusalem Post writes that it is expected that the United Arab Emirates will present a resolution calling on the United Nations Security Council to ensure Palestine status as a full member in the United Nations. The text, which will probably receive support from the majority, states that "Palestinian is qualified to become a member of the United Nations in accordance with Article 4 of the Charter and should therefore be admitted as a member of the United Nations."
&nbsp;
The Palestinian Authority, through the UAE, addressed the General Assembly after last month the United States had vetoed its request for membership of the Security Council. The United States is one of the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council with veto power. The resolution of the United Arab Emirates "recommends" that the Security Council "reconsiders favourably the question", but in essence, its text seeks to circumvent the exclusive power of the United Nations Security Council to determine membership to the United Nations. The resolutions of the United Nations General Assembly, however, cannot be vetoed, and the Palestinian Authority enjoys the automatic support of the majority in the General Assembly of the United Nations, where about 140 of its members recognize Palestine as a state independently.
&nbsp;
The UNGA does not have the formal power to ensure that Palestinians join the United Nations, but it can provide them with a de facto recognition which allows them to operate as a state within the United Nations system. In 2012, the United Nations General Assembly voted with 138 votes in favour and 9 against to ensure that Palestinians have non-member observer status. This move allows them to participate in the UN forums and sign many of its statutes and treaties, including the State of Rome, which governs the International Criminal Court. According to the current draft resolution, today the United Nations General Assembly would grant Palestine the right to operate within its plenum as a Member State, granting it almost everything except the right to vote, which would require the approval of the United Nations Security Council.
&nbsp;
The resolution states "the right of the Palestinian people to self-determination, including the right to their independent State of Palestine." In practice, the State of Palestine could be seated among the Member States and have extensive rights to speak to the plenum in its name or in the name of groups. The Palestinians could present resolutions, proposals and amendments on their own or on behalf of groups within the United Nations system. If the resolution was adopted, the Palestinians could also participate in high-level meetings and international conferences, where they would be entitled to vote.&nbsp;
<h2> Biden-Netanyahu spout, distance truce
Biden and Netanyahu are increasingly moving away, and hopes of a truce in Gaza are affected after yet nothing of the negotiations in Cairo. In an increase of tension the two allies have increased their distances, accomplices the American electoral round, but also internal pressure to the government of the Jewish State on the Israeli leader. The threats of the American president to block further shipments of weapons, if the Tel Aviv army should launch the great assault on the densely populated areas of Rafah, in southern Gaza, did not discourage the Israeli leader who was ready to continue in the Hamas annihilation alone.
&nbsp;
"Today we face again enemies willing to destroy us. I tell the world leaders: no pressure, no decision by any international forum will prevent Israel from defending itself" Netanyahu said yesterday on the occasion of the Holocaust memorial day in Jerusalem. "If Israel is forced to remain alone, it will. Countless people well around the world support our right cause - he added -. We will defeat our Genocide enemies." Strong words, when the high-level negotiations in Cairo, aimed at reaching a ceasefire and an agreement on the hostages, were escalated for the last time. The delegations left the Egyptian capital without reaching an agreement and the Palestinian militant group Hamas announced that now "the ball is completely in the hands of Israel".
&nbsp;
Tel Aviv, explained the movement in a note, rejected the proposal submitted by the mediators and "ha raised objections on different central issues". The efforts of Egypt and other mediators, Qatar and the United States, "continue to approach the points of view of the two parties," said with optimism a high-level Egyptian source. But already on Monday, Hamas had declared that he had accepted the proposal to cease fire by the mediators. An understanding that provided for the withdrawal of Israeli forces from Gaza, the return of displaced Palestinians because of the war and the exchange of hostages held by militants with Palestinian prisoners held in Israel, with the aim of a "death permanent fire". Proposed by Israel as "free from our essential demands".
&nbsp;
For the Jewish state, the priority remains to "destroy Hamas". "I address myself to the enemies of Israel, as well as to our best friends, and I say: the State of Israel cannot be submissive," said Israeli Defense Minister Yoav Gallant, adding that the country will do "everything necessary" to defend its citizens and "to resist those who try to destroy us."
&nbsp;
The concerns of the Biden administration have only increased since the tanks and Israeli troops entered the eastern part of Rafah on Monday night, occupying the main border crossing between Gaza and Egypt. Hence the position of the White House which continues to take more and more distances from the Israeli ally. In the evening spokesman Jonh Kirby said: "Irruption of Israel to Rafah will not be able to eradicate Hamas." So the Jewish state will have to find "alternative solutions to the long-term assault threatened against a city where more than a million Palestinians take refuge." Kirby also assured that the United States is still working with Israel on how to help him defeat the movement, such as ensuring that the border between Gaza and Egypt cannot be used for smuggling weapons and to target Hamas leaders.
&nbsp;
In addition, he added, while the United States temporarily suspended the transfer of bombs, Israel "is still receiving the vast majority of everything it needs to defend itself," and that a recent funding package approved by Congress will continue to send billions to Israel. And of this probably Netanyahu is aware. The premier, interviewed late in the evening by an American talk show threw water on the fire: "With Biden we often had agreements, but we also had disagreements. We were able to overcome them. I hope we will succeed now, but we will do what we have to do to protect our country," said the Israeli prime minister. &nbsp;

